## The Operational Challenge

Your system failed. You look at the metrics. The metrics show the failure. The metrics did not predict it.

Leading indicators are metrics that move before the failure. They give you time to act.

Here are the indicators that predict failure.

Having access to operational data is meaningless unless it drives decisions. Too many companies build static dashboards that sit ignored because they display trailing metrics instead of leading indicators. To build a data-driven culture, teams need active analytics loops that highlight immediate blockers and project capacity requirements.

## Core Pillars

* **Response time trend**: A system that responds in 200ms is fine. A system that responded in 100ms last month and 200ms this month is degrading. The trend predicts the failure.
* **Error rate trend**: A system that produces 2 errors a day is normal. A system that produced 2 errors a day last week and 3 errors a day this week is shifting. The shift predicts the failure.
* **Database query performance**: The queries that are getting slower. The index that is no longer used. The table that is growing faster than expected. The performance predicts the failure.
* **Queue depth trend**: A queue that sits at 10 items is normal. A queue that sat at 5 items last month and 10 items this month is backing up. The backup predicts the failure.

## Real-World Impact & Metrics

I tracked these indicators for a client in 2024. The system appeared healthy. But the trends were all negative. We investigated. The database was missing an index. The fix took two hours. The failure was prevented.

### Performance Comparison

| Metric | Before Redevise | After Redevise | Improvement |
| :--- | :--- | :--- | :--- |
| Billable Hours | Baseline | Optimized | Optimized |

> **Strategic Takeaway:** The teams that track absolute values are the ones that react to failures. The teams that track trends are the ones that prevent failures. Watch the response time trend. Watch the error rate trend. Watch the query performance. Watch the queue depth trend. The failure is predictable.

